the 7 properties of ribcage:
1 ENERGY one
2 PHASE advances slowly with the breath cycle
3 SPIN zero
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE one
6 COUPLING one with spine and the cardiopulmonary organs

THE TWELVE PAIRS OF RIBS

ribs one through seven are true ribs: each connects directly to the sternum at the front
ribs eight through ten are false ribs: their cartilage joins the seventh rib's cartilage rather than the sternum directly
ribs eleven and twelve are floating ribs: they have no anterior attachment, ending in the abdominal wall

each rib articulates with two adjacent thoracic vertebrae at the back, allowing the small movement that makes breathing possible

THE STERNUM

the sternum is the flat bone at the front center
manubrium at the top, body in the middle, xiphoid process at the bottom
the sternum is the keystone that holds the true ribs together at the front
sternum marrow continues to produce blood cells throughout life

THE COSTAL CARTILAGES

the ribs do not connect directly to the sternum; cartilage bridges the gap
this cartilage is what allows the rib cage to expand and contract during breathing
in fadriel at two, the costal cartilages are mostly cartilage, with ossification proceeding gradually over decades

THE CAVITY

inside the ribcage sits the thoracic cavity, divided by the diaphragm from the abdominal cavity below
the cavity contains heart, lungs, esophagus, major blood vessels, lymphatics
all of these are suspended by visceral fascia inside the cage's protected interior

VERB expand_in_inspiration
when diaphragm contracts, the ribcage rises and rotates outward
this increases thoracic volume, drawing air into the lungs
intercostal muscles between the ribs assist with this motion

VERB contract_in_expiration
when diaphragm relaxes, the ribcage falls and rotates inward by elastic recoil
this expels air from the lungs without active muscle work in normal breathing
forced exhalation engages internal intercostals to compress the cage further

VERB protect_thoracic_organs
the bony cage shields heart, lungs, and great vessels from impact
ribs can break under heavy load, but this is preferable to direct trauma to the organs they cover

VERB anchor_breathing_muscles
diaphragm attaches at the lower margin of the cage
intercostal muscles fill the spaces between adjacent ribs
many shoulder and neck muscles attach to the upper ribs

a ribcage is the body's most active bone structure
unlike spine which sustains, unlike skull which protects, unlike pelvis which transfers, ribcage moves twelve to twenty times per minute throughout fadriel's entire life
the cage is alive with motion; that motion is breath
